00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:55.930
It starts off with a review
of industrialization.

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:05.560
Some historians claim that there
have been three momentous times

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.320
in human history--

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:10.510
something in the
neolithic period,

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:15.850
something in the post-religion
period of the Enlightenment,

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:19.150
and the Industrial Revolution.

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:24.610
Nothing in my mind contests
with the Industrial Revolution.

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:32.740
And in a sense, except
for your own education,

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:37.870
anything prior to the
period from 1750 onwards

00:03:37.870 --> 00:03:39.770
is irrelevant.

00:03:39.770 --> 00:03:43.690
I know it's a stupid thing
to say but I'll say it again.

00:03:43.690 --> 00:03:49.840
From this class' point of
view, we start at 1750.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:54.220
And today, we will
try to understand

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:57.190
a very complex
phenomenon, the phenomenon

00:03:57.190 --> 00:04:04.480
[INAUDIBLE] which
increased almost

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:08.780
every aspect of human life,
particularly in England.

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:11.086
Why in England?

00:04:11.086 --> 00:04:14.830
[HEAVY SIGH] Enough
theorists have tried

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:16.344
to understand why in England.

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:26.100
I referred you in the
reading to a book by--

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:29.400
a recent book by
a man called Clark

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:34.080
from the West Coast university,
University of California

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.030
in Davis, I think.

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:38.820
The book is called
A Farewell to Arms.

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:46.500
Did you find any interesting
ideas in that book?

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:47.125
Let me explain.

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:54.120
The Industrial
Revolution, as I was

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.790
confronted with it is
a high school student

00:04:56.790 --> 00:05:00.630
and then at
university, was a set

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:06.300
of events by
people, individuals,

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:17.430
who transformed the built
world, from Telford in Newcastle

00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:20.115
using steel to--

00:05:23.110 --> 00:05:29.580
not Telford-- sorry, Stephenson
in Newcastle, learning how to--

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:35.070
teaching us how to
industrialize the railroad.

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:44.820
McAdam, from which we
learn how to pave roads.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:47.760
From 1901, the first
British census,

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:53.400
we learned the value of
establishing a uniform system

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:56.910
for counting how many
people are in the nation.

00:05:56.910 --> 00:05:59.400
The penny postage stamp--

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:06.540
the first stamp which
allowed communication by mail

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:11.970
in a systematic manner, and so
on and on and on and on and on

00:06:11.970 --> 00:06:14.040
and on and on.

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:15.650
Nobody explains why it happened.

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:22.740
The theory is the
genius of human beings

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:29.160
all lumped together changed
the British landscape.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:32.100
However, we can't be that naive.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:35.520
We have to ask ourselves
deeper questions,

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:38.880
because these
changes are serious

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:41.610
and affected the world
in significant ways.

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:56.000
Clark's book argues
that, in a crude sense,

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:04.100
the world in England in 1200
was a world securing property,

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:12.680
free trade, all of the
basic economic conditions

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:19.860
which initiative
could take place.

00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:22.310
In fact, [INAUDIBLE] a table
in the book, if you ever

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:31.780
read the book, which compares
1200 England with 2000 England

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:38.230
and shows the metaconditions
were the same.

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:42.670
What he argues of, which
is novel in this argument

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:49.230
about the Industrial
Revolution, that there

00:07:49.230 --> 00:07:54.060
was a transmission, either
culturally or biogenetically,

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:59.880
from the wealthy, who
had bigger families

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:06.150
and who lived longer,
through a downward mobility

00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:08.190
to the rest of the population.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:18.190
And he cites a
number of conditions,

00:08:18.190 --> 00:08:27.910
having examined the wills
of people from 1200 to 1800.

00:08:27.910 --> 00:08:32.780
He derives a number
of conclusions--

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:38.789
that the world changed
for the people en masse.

00:08:38.789 --> 00:08:40.890
Interest rates fell.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.530
Murder rates declined.

00:08:43.530 --> 00:08:45.120
Work hours increased.

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:50.870
Taste for violence declined.

00:08:55.530 --> 00:09:00.930
Education spread to
the lower classes.

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:02.640
And savings increased.

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:08.340
In the handout today,
I gave you a review.

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:11.340
There have been many
reviews of this book--

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:14.170
some arguing with it,
some saying it's nonsense,

00:09:14.170 --> 00:09:15.900
some saying it has some basis.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:22.200
But Clark has not concluded
that it's biogenetic or cultural

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.370
or how the transmission
actually took place.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:32.450
What is powerful about his
argument is that it's new.

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:35.230
It's fresh.

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:41.875
It's much more vigorous
than previous examples.

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:47.995
The taste for violence declined.

00:09:51.830 --> 00:10:02.990
In 1851, boxing was
conditioned by weight.

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:09.230
In medieval boxing,
a big man seven

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:12.360
foot tall, boxed
somebody three foot tall.

00:10:12.360 --> 00:10:14.184
And everybody laughed.

00:10:14.184 --> 00:10:19.940
[LAUGHTER] I will cite you,
when we talk about Paris,

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:24.545
about the burning of cats in
public space to amuse people.

00:10:28.190 --> 00:10:31.970
The tradition of beating up
animals through cockfighting,

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:38.450
bullfighting, and so
on declined and was

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:42.740
replaced by a rationalized
form of sport.

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:47.450
Manchester United was
formed as a club in 1878.

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:51.470
Today it's the wealthiest
sporting franchise

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:53.930
in the world.

00:10:53.930 --> 00:10:58.640
Manchester, where Engels wrote
The Condition of the Working

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:02.630
Class in England, was hardly
the site, according to Engels,

00:11:02.630 --> 00:11:07.610
for the emergence of a $100
billion sports franchise.

00:11:14.770 --> 00:11:16.465
Taste for violence declined.

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:25.840
How do you explain how a
taste for violence can be--

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:28.810
this country, at the
moment, is engaged

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:31.690
in trying to deal with
what we could only

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:38.240
call a culture of violence,
in which violence seems

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:43.160
to be built into the
grain of the society

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:46.160
in a way which is
difficult to understand

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:48.260
and difficult to
do something about.

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:53.500
How do these changes take place?

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.600
And how aware were
those of us who

00:11:55.600 --> 00:12:00.760
were preoccupied with
making decisions for people

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:03.370
about the cities they live in?

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:07.960
How do we understand
these cultural shifts?

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.700
I grew up as a modernist.

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:15.460
When I look at the work
I did as a student,

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:20.130
both in architecture and in
city planning, I'm embarrassed.

00:12:20.130 --> 00:12:22.360
The culture in
which I worked was

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:26.250
very different from the
one in which you work now.

00:12:33.220 --> 00:12:35.410
We can only understand--

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:38.200
and I'm not going
to deal extensively

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:43.250
with societal changes in
this period in England.

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:45.430
I'm only going to
deal with them when

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:50.730
they affect some notion about
the built form of places.

00:12:50.730 --> 00:12:55.600
Otherwise, we'd be here, and
I'm incompetent to give you

00:12:55.600 --> 00:13:01.700
a very good background in
19th century English history.

00:13:01.700 --> 00:13:04.330
I'm just going to pick
on certain coincidences

00:13:04.330 --> 00:13:05.650
and events.

00:13:14.144 --> 00:13:23.310
For instance, Peterloo was
a gathering of protesters

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:26.610
in Liverpool, I
think it was, just

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:30.660
after the British won the
great battle against Napoleon

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:32.970
in Waterloo.

00:13:32.970 --> 00:13:40.130
11 Englishmen were killed by
the police and the military.

00:13:40.130 --> 00:13:48.270
152 years later, 13 Englishmen--
actually, Catholic Irish--

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:52.020
were killed by the British
police and military.

00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:57.780
Over a period of 152 years of
this incredible transformation

00:13:57.780 --> 00:14:01.320
of the society, the British
police and the military

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:04.860
didn't kill more
than 11 or 13 people.

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:09.925
It's a remarkable story.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:17.410
And in it the origins
of Marxist thought

00:14:17.410 --> 00:14:22.090
fits quite neatly, which I will
talk a bit about later when we

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:23.980
deal with Engels in Manchester.

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:35.670
Clark makes a big story
about the Malthusian trap.

00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:40.350
Malthus wrote a book in 1798--

00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:41.670
I forget the title.

00:14:41.670 --> 00:14:42.940
I used to know the title.

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:45.770
Does anybody know the
title of Malthus' book?

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:47.520
AUDIENCE: The dismal
science [INAUDIBLE]??

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:48.478
JULIAN BEINART: No, no.

00:14:48.478 --> 00:14:52.560
That's what it was
called by critics.

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:56.770
It's something about
the population.

00:14:56.770 --> 00:15:02.940
Essentially, the Malthusian
trap, Clark argues,

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:06.630
is that, until the
Industrial Revolution,

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:11.220
the amount of food that would
be produced in a society

00:15:11.220 --> 00:15:15.360
or in a city or in a village
was equal to the amount

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:18.660
of population that could be fed.

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:26.070
If there was an innovation
in the society's production,

00:15:26.070 --> 00:15:30.210
incomes rose, but the
population stayed the same

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:35.490
because the food
supply wasn't enlarged.

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:42.540
Malthus in 1798m as I will
show you in the graph,

00:15:42.540 --> 00:15:46.560
observed the most rapid
change in percentage

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:51.060
of population increase
that Britain had ever seen.

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:56.160
Manchester was increasing in
population by 10% per annum,

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:02.940
whereas European birth rates or
growth rates, population growth

00:16:02.940 --> 00:16:05.740
rates, largely
because of disease

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:11.085
over the medieval period,
averaged about 0.6% or 1%.

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:22.990
Trevelyan, one of the great
British historians, I quote--

00:16:22.990 --> 00:16:26.410
"The survival of many more
infants and the prolongation

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:29.740
of the average age of adults
marks off modern times

00:16:29.740 --> 00:16:31.060
from the past.

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:36.900
And this change begins
in the 19th century."

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:42.840
Two phenomenon-- death
rate, people live longer,

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:45.840
and more children survive.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:48.840
Put those two together, and
you have the fundamentals

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:52.320
of population growth.

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:06.170
In 1500, London's population
was between 40,000 and 60,000

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:07.910
people.

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:14.210
Paris was already had a
population of about 200,000.

00:17:14.210 --> 00:17:20.210
So London was almost the
second great European city.

00:17:20.210 --> 00:17:25.280
By 1851 or 1850, it was the
largest city in the world,

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:29.120
with an estimated population of
2 to 2 and 1/2 million people.

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:40.030
1851 is the signal date in
the 19th century for us.

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:45.530
What happened in 1851,
or around about 1850?

00:17:45.530 --> 00:17:49.040
The most significant
building of the 19th century

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:54.680
was built in London,
the Crystal Palace.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:58.820
Who is the chairman
of the committee?

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:01.256
And who built the
Crystal Palace?

00:18:01.256 --> 00:18:02.960
AUDIENCE: It was Paxton, right?

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:07.970
JULIAN BEINART: Paxton was
chosen by James Cubitt.

00:18:07.970 --> 00:18:12.380
Cubitt was the first
Industrial builder.

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:17.570
Instead of using medieval
feudal labor, journeymen,

00:18:17.570 --> 00:18:21.230
on a daily basis, he
employed up to 1,000 people

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:24.230
on permanent salaries.

00:18:24.230 --> 00:18:29.780
He believed, like many of
these progressive individuals,

00:18:29.780 --> 00:18:34.310
that architects were
second rate and [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:34.310 --> 00:18:39.440
in their behavior.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:41.690
Cubitt, for instance,
advised the queen,

00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:45.860
who wanted to develop a large
part of the Isle of Wight,

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:48.170
I think it was, if I'm correct.

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:50.210
I'm trying to remember.

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.770
He said, don't use architects.

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:53.720
They just waste your time.

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:57.290
Baron Haussmann in Paris
did exactly the same thing.

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:14.110
1850-- England was,
for the first time,

00:19:14.110 --> 00:19:19.060
divided into 50% of the
population living in cities

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:21.746
and 50% living in rural area.

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:39.550
A trivial event, the invention
of camera processing,

00:19:39.550 --> 00:19:43.600
the capacity to
photograph, to make

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:46.915
recordings of the built world--

00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:55.680
the conquering of disease.

00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:16.200
In 1854, a physician
in London decided

00:20:16.200 --> 00:20:22.380
that cholera, which is the most
prevalent and most dangerous

00:20:22.380 --> 00:20:28.470
of urban diseases, was not born
in the air but was water borne.

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:35.280
These are pieces we are
reading for next Tuesday, which

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:39.690
deals with this, and
followed by the biggest

00:20:39.690 --> 00:20:46.380
piece of infrastructure
yet built in the world to--

00:20:46.380 --> 00:20:51.240
imagine living in [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:51.240 --> 00:20:56.130
Manchester in 1830,
the city couldn't

00:20:56.130 --> 00:21:01.320
get people, municipal workers,
to go into their houses.

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:05.310
They had to open the windows
first, break the windows

00:21:05.310 --> 00:21:08.100
to let in fresh air.

00:21:08.100 --> 00:21:13.470
The British parliament had
to be stopped one summer

00:21:13.470 --> 00:21:16.010
because the smell was so bad.

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:21.600
London rivers was so polluted,
all the garbage and sewage

00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:25.680
and feces produced
by the English

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:29.100
in London, in a city of two
million people, went straight

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:30.990
into the river.

00:21:30.990 --> 00:21:35.280
People made a living picking
up bones in the river.

00:21:35.280 --> 00:21:38.190
This is the first chapter
of the book called The Ghost

00:21:38.190 --> 00:21:43.560
Map, which deals with the
invention of the cholera

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:45.120
phenomenon--

00:21:45.120 --> 00:21:47.070
not the invention
of the phenomenon,

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:50.100
the invention of the cure--

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:55.500
which details that
concept of life in London.

